# Finance Data Processing and Access Control — Full Stack (Backend Focused)

> **Submission by:** Bhukya Ramprakash · chitti852852@gmail.com
> **Role Applied:** Backend Developer Intern

---

## What This Project Is

This project is a backend system built as part of the assignment to demonstrate practical backend engineering skills, including system design, data modeling, access control, API design, and reliable data processing.

The implementation focuses on:
- Designing a clear and structured backend architecture  
- Modeling financial data accurately  
- Enforcing role-based access control (RBAC)  
- Building APIs for both CRUD operations and aggregated insights  
- Handling validation and errors consistently  
- Maintaining clean, modular, and readable code  

The system is designed not just to function correctly, but to reflect how a backend should be structured in real-world scenarios—emphasizing clarity, maintainability, and logical organization.

As an additional enhancement beyond the assignment requirements, a minimal frontend was implemented to interact with the backend. This allows easier testing and visualization of features such as RBAC, transaction management, and dashboard analytics without relying solely on tools like Postman. The frontend is intended only as a supporting layer, while the primary focus remains on backend design and implementation.


> The assignment asks for a backend. The frontend is an additional layer built to make the system tangible and testable without needing Postman — every backend feature (RBAC, validation, aggregation) is visible directly in the browser.

---

## Tech Stack & Why

### Backend

| Layer | Choice | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Runtime | Node.js + Express | Lightweight, well-understood for REST APIs, excellent ecosystem |
| Database | PostgreSQL | Financial data is relational by nature; ACID guarantees matter |
| ORM | Prisma | Schema-as-code doubles as living documentation; migrations are version-controlled |
| Validation | Zod | Composable schemas that are also readable documentation; errors map to field names |
| Auth | JWT (jsonwebtoken) | Stateless, standard; no session storage needed for this scope |
| Password hashing | bcryptjs | Cost factor 12 — production-safe balance of speed and security |

**One decision I want to highlight:** I chose `Decimal` over `Float` for the `amount` field in Prisma. Float uses IEEE 754 arithmetic, which means `0.1 + 0.2 = 0.30000000000000004`. For any financial system, even at assessment scale, this is the wrong choice. `Decimal @db.Decimal(12,2)` stores exact values.

### Frontend

| Layer | Choice | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Framework | React 18 + Vite | Component model maps cleanly to role-based UI; Vite gives instant HMR |
| Styling | Tailwind CSS | Utility classes keep styles co-located with markup; no context switching |
| Server state | React Query | Handles caching, loading, and error states for every API call automatically |
| Routing | React Router v6 | Protected route + Outlet pattern mirrors the backend's RBAC structure |
| Charts | Recharts | React-native, composable; bar and doughnut charts with minimal config |
| HTTP client | Axios | Interceptors attach JWT headers globally and handle 401 auto-logout |
| Forms | React Hook Form | Minimal re-renders, pairs well with native HTML validation |
| Toasts | react-hot-toast | Lightweight feedback for create/delete/error events |

---

## Architecture

```
Browser (React SPA)
  └── Axios (JWT interceptor + auto-logout on 401)
        └── Express Router
              ├── Auth Middleware   (JWT verification + active user check)
              ├── RBAC Middleware   (permission string check)
              └── Controller
                    └── Service         (business logic)
                          └── Repository    (all Prisma queries)
                                └── PostgreSQL
```

**Backend layers:** Each layer has a single responsibility. Controllers handle HTTP in/out. Services contain business rules. Repositories own every database call — nothing outside the repository layer touches Prisma directly.

**Frontend layers:** Pages call API functions (never Axios directly). React Query manages server state, caching, and refetch. The `RoleGuard` component mirrors the backend's RBAC — pages render a 403 view for insufficient roles without making the API call at all.

---

## Role & Permission Design

Rather than checking role names inline (`if role === 'ADMIN'`), I built a **permission map**. Each role maps to an array of permission strings:

```js
const PERMISSIONS = {
  ADMIN:   ['read:users', 'write:users', 'delete:users',
            'read:transactions', 'write:transactions', 'delete:transactions',
            'read:dashboard'],
  ANALYST: ['read:transactions', 'read:dashboard'],
  VIEWER:  ['read:dashboard'],
};
```

The RBAC middleware checks these strings, not role names:

```js
export const authorize = (...required) => (req, res, next) => {
  const userPerms = PERMISSIONS[req.user.role] ?? [];
  const allowed   = required.every(p => userPerms.includes(p));
  if (!allowed) return res.status(403).json({ ... });
  next();
};
```

**Why this matters:** Adding a new role in the future means adding one entry to the map. No route files, controllers, or service logic changes. The permission check is explicit, readable, and centralized.

